revision.text:
{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}} {{Infobox book | name = A Tourist Guide to Lancre | title_orig = | translator = | image = File:Discworld tourist guide.jpg | caption = Cover | author = [[Terry Pratchett]] and [[Stephen Briggs]] | illustrator = [[Paul Kidby]] | cover_artist = [[Paul Kidby]] | country = Great Britain | language = English | series = [[Discworld]] | subject = | genre = [[Fantasy]] | publisher = [[Corgi Books]] | pub_date = 1998 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print | pages = | isbn = 0-552-14608-0 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = [[The Discworld Mapp]] | followed_by = [[Death's Domain]] }} '''''A Tourist Guide To Lancre''''' is the third book in the ''[[Discworld]] Mapp'' series, and the first to be illustrated by [[Paul Kidby]]. As with the other maps, the basic design and booklet were compiled by [[Terry Pratchett]] and [[Stephen Briggs]].
The Mapp shows the mountain country of [[Lancre]], with the [[Ramtops]] drawn in a vertigo-inducing perspective shot, rather than as a relief diagram. The accompanying booklet details the history, geography and folklore of the country, with contributions from both [[Nanny Ogg|Gytha Ogg]] (anticipating the style of ''[[Nanny Ogg's Cookbook]]'') and Eric Wheelbrace, the [[Discworld (world)|Discworld]]'s most famous hillwalker (a parody of [[Alfred Wainwright]]).
