__NOTOC__ [[File:Kunstgewerbemuseum Berlin Kulturforum entrance.jpg|thumb|277x277px|The entrance to the Kunstgewerbemuseum at the [[Kulturforum]]]] [[File:Kunstgewerbemuseum Berlin Kulturforum staircases.jpg|thumb|240x240px|Inside the Kunstgewerbemuseum]] The '''Kunstgewerbemuseum''', or '''Museum of Decorative Arts''', is an internationally important museum of the [[decorative arts]] in [[Berlin]], [[Germany]], part of the [[Staatliche Museen zu Berlin]] (Berlin State Museums). The collection is split between the Kunstgewerbemuseum building at the [[Kulturforum]] {{nowrap|({{coord|52.5097|13.3674|type:landmark_region:DE|display=inline,title|name=Kunstgewerbemuseum, Kulturforum}})}} and [[Köpenick Palace]] {{nowrap|({{coord|52.4439|13.5728|type:landmark_region:DE|display=inline|name=Kunstgewerbemuseum, Schloss Köpenick}}).}}
==History== It was founded in 1868 as the ''Deutsches Gewerbe-Museum zu Berlin'', and originally had a [[Kunstgewerbeschule|teaching institute]] as well as a public museum. The collection grew significantly in the 1870s, and it was renamed ''Kunstgewerbemuseum'' in 1879. In 1881 it relocated into the [[Martin-Gropius-Bau]] – where [[Priam's Treasure]] was also on display for a time – and in 1921 it moved into the [[Stadtschloss, Berlin|Stadtschloss]].<ref name=zeit>[http://www.zeit.de/2009/21/Museumsfuehrer Heute mal Extremitäten] Tobias Timm, ''[[Die Zeit]]'', 31 August 2009. Retrieved 26 September 2010. {{de icon}}</ref> [[File:Schloss Koepenick Hofseite.jpg|thumb|[[Köpenick Palace|Köpenick palace]] ]] Parts of the collection were destroyed in World War II,<ref>[http://www.smb.museum/smb/standorte/index.php?lang=de&p=2&objID=37&n=8 Kunstgewerbemuseum] [[Berlin State Museums]]. {{de icon}}</ref> and the surviving items were split between [[East Berlin|East]] and [[West Berlin]].<ref name="zeit" /> The Eastern collection moved into Köpenick Palace in 1963, while the Western exhibits moved first into [[Charlottenburg Palace]], then into the new museum building in the Kulturforum<ref>[http://www.kulturforum-berlin.com/extrafenster/kunstgewerbemuseum.html Kunstgewerbemuseum] [[Kulturforum]]. {{de icon}}</ref> in 1985, built by [[Rolf Gutbrod]].
==Exhibition==
The Kunstgewerbemuseum displays European (and [[Byzantine art|Byzantine]]) decorative arts from all post-classical periods of art history, and features gold, silver, glass and [[enamelware|enamel]] items, [[porcelain]], furniture, [[panelling]], [[tapestry]], costumes, and silks.<ref name=home>[http://www.smb.spk-berlin.de/smb/sammlungen/details.php?lang=en&objID=7 Museum of Decorative Arts] {{en icon}}</ref>[[Image:Gropius Bau Berlin 1.jpg|thumb|The north wing of the former Kunstgewerbemuseum (today [[Martin-Gropius-Bau]]), which for many years accommodated the Unterrichtsanstalt des Kunstgewerbemuseums Berlin ("teaching institute")]]There is a very important collection of [[Late Antique]] objects in many media. The items from the [[Middle Ages]] include a large number of gold [[Reliquary|reliquaries]]. The [[Renaissance]] is represented by silverware from the city councillors of [[Lüneburg]], and [[bronze sculpture]]s, tapestries, furniture, [[Venetian glass]]es and [[maiolica]]s from the Italian princely courts.<ref name="home" />
The [[Baroque]] era is represented by [[faience]]s from [[Delft]], and glass items. There is also European porcelain (particularly from [[Meissen porcelain|Meissen]] and the Royal Manufacturer of Berlin), and decorative crockery from the [[rococo]], [[Classicism|classicist]], [[Historicism|historicist]] and [[Art Nouveau]] styles. The "New Collection" of 20th century craftwork includes industrially-manufactured products.<ref name="home" />
