{{unreferenced|date=March 2018}}

{{Linguistic typology topics}}

An '''oligoisolating language''' (from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] {{lang|grc|ὀλίγος}}, meaning "few" or "little") is any [[language]] using very few [[morpheme]]s which tend towards [[isolating languages|an isolating structure]] of statements. Oligoisolation is almost entirely theoretical and would necessitate long, modifier-heavy sentences.

No natural language has oligoisolating properties; nevertheless it is present in some [[constructed language]]s, such as [[Toki Pona]] and [[aUI (language)|aUI]].

==See also==
* [[Oligosynthetic language]]
* [[Semantic primitives]]

